12. The literary tendency of the times, as well as his own inclination, led the poet to devote his activity to the sabula palliata. Terence produced his first comcdy, the Andria, at the Indi Meqalenses, in April, 166 Bc The aediles, who had charge of the games, had some misgivings about allowing the presentation of a play by an entirely unknown poet. He was accordingly induced to submit his play first to the older poet Caecilius, for approval. Regard- ing the meeting between these two poets, the following story is told. Terence found Caecilius at dinner, and, as the caller was meanly dressed, he was given a seat on a bench near the conch on which the great author was reclin- ing, and was then given permission to read what he had written. After the first few verses had been read, Caecilius was so captivated by the young man's talents that he in- vited him to a place beside him upon the couch. He then listened attentively and with unbounded admiration to the remainder of the play.
